<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kukan Assesses Egyptian, Syrian Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kukan Assesses Egyptian, Syrian Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606193394 Bratislava STV 1 Television Network in Slovak 
1730 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2606193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava STV 1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on an interview with Slovak Foreign Affairs Minister </F>
Eduard Kukan by an unidentified correspondent; place and date 
not given] 
  [Text] Eduard Kukan said that his official visit to three 
Arab countries, which to a certain extent followed the January 
official visit to Israel of Jozef Moravcik, who was then Slovak 
foreign minister, had two main objectives. 
  The first was to demonstrate Slovak support for the Middle 
East peace process, although our country does not overestimate 
its influence on developments in this region. What was more 
important was to demonstrate interest in developing mutual 
relations, which had been stagnating after the demise of 
Czechoslovakia, as well as a certain enhancement of the economic 
dimension of our foreign policy. 
  The Arab world is a prospective trade partner and is very 
interested in cooperating with our country. This was confirmed, 
among other things, for example, during the talks our foreign 
minister had with Egyptian President Mubarak and Syrian 
President al-Asad. 
  It should be added in this connection that the Slovak 
economy 
has a chance of stepping up cooperation with the Palestinian 
autonomous regions, which will start building their 
infrastructure in the near future. Through Egypt or Jordan, our 
companies might start getting involved even in this direction. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

