<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Owen on Danger of `All-Out War' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Owen on Danger of `All-Out War' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606112594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1032 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2606112594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Zagreb, Jun 26 (TANJUG) -- Lord David Owen, the 
European Union's mediator for the former Yugoslavia, has warned 
of a danger of the conflicts in Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina 
turning into an all-out war against the Serbs in both of the 
former Yugoslav republics. 
  Lord Owen and the other co-chairman of the international 
conference on the former Yugoslavia, U.N. mediator Thorvald 
Stoltenberg, arrived in the Croatian capital of Zagreb on 
Saturday evening for talks with Croatian President Franjo 
Tudjman. 
  Lord Owen told the press in Zagreb that "if things went 
wrong 
in Bosnia, there is always a danger of the Bosnian and Croatian 
Serbs link-up, and (of) the Croats and Muslims, and another big 
war involving both Bosnia and Croatia". 
  Serbs proclaimed their national states on historically and 
ethnically their territories in Croatia -- the republic of Serb 
Krajina (RSK), and in Bosnia-Herzegovina -- the Srpska republic 
(R.S.) in late 1991 and 1992, respectively, that is, after the 
two republics forcibly seceded from the former Yugoslav 
Federation. 
  Lord Owen said that the main topic of the Zagreb talks was 
how to renew the talks between the RSK Serbs and Croatian 
authorities. 
  Lord Owen set out that no date had been set for a new round 
of Croat-Serb talks, which were put off last on June 16. 
  The international negotiator underscored that the talks must 
be held separately from those between the Bosnian Muslims, Serbs 
and Croats. 
  The co-chairmen of the international conference on the 
former 
Yugoslavia visited the capital of The Former Yugoslav Republic 
of Macedonia (FYROM), Skopje, and Belgrade before arriving in 
Zagreb. They conferred with FYROM President Kiro Gligorov and 
President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

