<H3> <TI>   Turkish Defense Ministry Delegation Visits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Turkish Defense Ministry Delegation Visits </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606201194 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1730 
GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2606201194 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A delegation of the Turkish Defense Ministry, led by 
Colonel General Teoman Ekran, this morning arrived on a two-day 
visit to the Croatian Defense Ministry. 
  They were welcomed at Zagreb airport by their host Brigadier 
General Antun Tus, military adviser to the Croatian president. 
  On the first day of their visit to Croatia the Turkish 
delegation visited the naval institute in Zagreb. 
  [Begin recording] [Tus] The aim of the visit is come to know 
each other better, to see at what technical and technological 
level we are both at, what production lines we have, what 
expertise and scientific potential we have and to achieve some 
cooperation in future related to the development and production 
of certain systems included in general economic programs and, 
certainly also, some programs which can be significant for the 
defense of the country. [end recording] 
  Questions related to the security in this part of Europe 
were 
also discussed. Croatia's integration in Partnership for Peace 
as soon as possible was on the agenda. 
  The talks are just the beginning of the cooperation between 
the two countries, Col-Gen Teoman Ekran said. 
  [Begin recording] [Ekran, speaking in Turkish, with 
superimposed Croatian translation] As you know, the Republic of 
Turkey was one of the first countries to recognize the Republic 
of Croatia. This is a model start for the future cooperation 
between the two countries. Turkey supports Croatian peace 
efforts for the resolution of the crisis in Bosnia and lends its 
full support to the Bosnia-Herzegovina federation. 
  After the visit to the naval institute the Turkish 
delegation 
visited Koncar complex. Visits to Karlovac and Turanj are 
scheduled for tomorrow as well as talks with Croatian Defense 
Minister Gojko Susak. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

