<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Criticizes International Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic Criticizes International Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606150494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1310 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2606150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Banja Luka, 26 Jun (TANJUG) -- The first generation 
of officers of the republic of Srpska army and the Serb army of 
Krajina in Croatia was promoted at a ceremony in the Center of 
Military Academies in Banja Luka today. The first officers who 
attended the academy were promoted to the rank of lieutenant 
colonel. The second generation of noncommissioned officers of 
the two armies were also promoted. 
  The ceremony was attended by Radovan Karadzic, supreme 
commander of the republic of Srpska army and president of the 
republic of Srpska, Colonel-General Ratko Mladic, chief of 
general staff of the republic of Srpska army, Major General 
Milan Celeketic, chief of general staff of the Serb army of 
Krajina, many other guests, and thousands of Banja Luka 
citizens, as well as the new officers' families and friends. 
  Addressing the newly promoted officers, Radovan Karadzic 
said 
that the humiliation of allowing the international community to 
draw its maps and offer them under the "take it or leave it" 
principle was unacceptable. "We want to end this war. Our aim 
so far has been to defend our own territory, but if our enemies 
and the international community are forcing us into a 
counteroffensive, we will not stop," Karadzic stressed. 
  Colonel General Ratko Mladic, Major General Milan Celeketic, 
and Major General Slavko Lisica, head of the center of military 
academies in Banja Luka, also spoke at the ceremony. The Center 
of Military Academies in Banja Luka was opened last year in the 
premises of the former Petar Drapsin Training Center for 
Armored-Motorized Units. Personnel from the republic of Srpska 
and the republic of Serb Krajina are trained there to become 
officers and noncommissioned officers. 

</TEXT>

