<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Seeks Gorazde Meeting With Military Leaders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Seeks Gorazde Meeting With Military Leaders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2706115094 Paris AFP in English 1131 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2706115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bruno Franceschi] </F>
  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, June 27 (AFP) -- UN officials were 
seeking a meeting with Bosnian Serb and Moslem military leaders 
Monday following the killing of a British UN soldier by 
suspected Serb gunners and other attacks on peacekeepers in the 
eastern enclave of Gorazde. Commander Eric Chaperon, spokesman 
for the UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR), said the unidentified 
soldier was killed Sunday evening at his observation post in 
Gorazde, probably by Serb gunners. His death brought to 44 the 
number of peacekeepers killed in Bosnia-Hercegovina in the past 
two years. "Sunday was a really bad day for the UN in Gorazde," 
Chaperon said. He said UN patrols in the region had come under 
repeated attack by Serb and Moslem gunners throughout the 
weekend, but no further casualties were reported. [passage 
omitted] 
  Elsewhere, artillery duels continued Monday in the northern 
Mount Ozren region, where the Moslem-led Bosnian army has been 
waging a major offensive against Serb forces, but the fighting 
was less intense than over the weekend, Chaperon said. "It is 
clear that the Bosnian troops have made territorial gains," he 
said although he couldn't provide any more details. 
  The Serbs have reportedly evacuated several villages in the 
area in the face of the Moslem offensive. 
  Chaperon said UN military observers deployed in the north 
were reporting heavy shelling from both sides. The observers 
were finding it increasingly difficult to accomplish their 
mission as they are not being granted access to the battle 
zones, he said. The fighting is in a strategic zone just south 
of a thin land corridor linking Serb-conquered territory in 
northeast and western Bosnia. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

