<H3> <TI>   Muslims Boycott Truce Extension Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims Boycott Truce Extension Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2506201194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1837 GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2506201194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, June 25 (TANJUG) -- Moslems refused to 
meet Bosnian Serb army representatives for U.N.-sponsored talks 
at Sarajevo airport on Saturday [25 June]. U.N. spokesman Rob 
Annink said the United Nations would try to organise another 
meeting between the Bosnian belligerents on Sunday to negotiate 
an extension to the four-month truce, REUTERS said. U.N. 
observers blamed Moslem snipers for the death of a Serb woman 
and a Serb soldier in Sarajevo on Friday. Annink told reporters 
that Moslem snipers were responsible for a number of ceasefire 
provocations and violations on Friday. 
  Moslem forces have been disregarding the one-month 
ceasefire, 
which was signed in Geneva on June 8 and took effect on June 10, 
and have continued to attack Bosnian Serb territories. On 
Thursday, Moslem forces commander Rasim Delic urged the new 
allies -- Bosnian Croats -- to mount an all-out war against the 
Serbs. Moslems and Croats, who had fought bitterly for 
territories since early 1993, succumbed to strong U.S. pressure 
in Washington on March 18 and agreed to form a federation in 
Bosnia, which should eventually form a confederation with 
neighbouring Croatia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

