<H3> <TI>   Serbian Minister: Solution `in U.S. Hands' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbian Minister: Solution `in U.S. Hands' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606152494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1447 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2606152494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kragujevac, 26 Jun (TANJUG) -- Aleksa Buha, foreign 
minister of the republic of Srpska, told Kragujevac radio today 
that "a conceptual muddle" regarding the resolution of the 
crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina continues. To the correspondent's 
remark that the formula is "take it or leave it" and that the 
lifting of the arms embargo and a continued implementation of 
the sanctions are proposed if the Serbian side does not accept 
the formula, Buha said that the international community has been 
warned hundreds of times that the conflict could then assume 
unforseeable proportions, as Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev has warned. 
  "I do not believe that the international community will 
allow 
things to get out of hand and take that course if the plan is 
not accepted. It is more likely that pressure will be put on 
all sides to reach a compromise, and perhaps a solution will be 
found within the new proposal, but with certain corrections. I 
believe the whole matter is in U.S. hands," Buha said. He said 
everything will become clearer in the next fortnight, after a 
series of talks. 
  "The solution lies in the recognition of the three peoples' 
right to self-determination, that is, to having their states and 
territorial borders, and after that all sovereign nations would 
establish the sort of relations that suit them," Buha said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

