<H3> <TI>   Fierce Inter-Muslim Fighting Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fierce Inter-Muslim Fighting Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606115694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1053 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2606115694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  Petrovac, June 26 (TANJUG) -- Fierce inter-Muslim clashes 
in the Cazin Krajina, north-western part of the former Yugoslav 
republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, are in their fifteenth day. 
Radio Velkaton, based in Velika Kladusa, the centre of the 
Muslim autonomous province of West Bosnia (APZB), reported on 
Sunday that troops loyal to fundamentalist leader Alija 
Izetbegovic were not chosing means in an effort to enter the 
territory held by APZB forces. According to the same source, 
there are dead, wounded and captured on both sides. 
  Radio Bihac, held by Izetbegovic's supporters, said that 
forces loyal to APZB President Fikret Abdic unsuccessfully 
attempted a number of infantry breakthroughs on the night of 
June 25-26 and Sunday morning. The APZB was proclaimed in 1993 
on the basis of the outcome of a referendum held in the Cazin 
Krajina, which is predominantlx populated by Muslims. Shortly 
after, President Abdic, a successful local businessman, signed 
peace accords with the Bosnian Serbs and Croats. 
  There followed an outbreak of fighting between APZB troops 
and troops loyal to Izetbegovic. Several hundred people have 
been killed in the inter-Muslim fighting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

