<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Observers Foresee Battle for Corridor </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Observers Foresee Battle for Corridor </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2606164394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1632 GMT 26 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2606164394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, June 26 (TANJUG) -- Moslems have been 
attacking Serb positions south of Doboj (northern Bosnia) for 
weeks, violating the June 10 truce, a U.N. spokesman said in 
Sarajevo on Sunday [26 June]. Major Rob Annink, spokesman for 
the U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR), is quoted by REUTERS as 
saying that the `(Moslem) army seems to have gained some 
territory around Zavidovici, about three to four kilometres 
worth.' Annink said that the Moslems had captured some 
territory also around Ribnica, Serb town near Tuzla in the 
north, on the road to Sarajevo. 
  U.N. observers registered 1,700 explosions between Ribnica 
and Doboj, a stretch of 45 kilometres, on Saturday. Observers 
believe that the fighting is a prelude to a full-scale battle 
for control of the northern corridor through the Posavina (Sava 
river valley) region which links the east and west of the 
Bosnian Serb republic. Flouting the one-month Bosnia-wide 
truce, Moslem Army Commander Rasim Delic on Thursday urged that 
the Moslems and their new allies -- the Croats -- join forces 
and mount an all-out war against the Serbs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

