<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bitola Power Plant Expands Capacity </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bitola Power Plant Expands Capacity </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94P20911A Skopje VECER in Macedonian 19 May 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20911A </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje VECER </F>
<F P=105>  Macedonian </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Editorial Report] S. Padori reports on the expanding 
capacity of the REK (Republic Electric Power Combine) "Bitola" 
in an article on page 7 in the Macedonian-language Skopje daily 
VECER, published on 19 May. The Bitola plant, which is the 
largest in The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM), 
will expand its generating capacity by 45 megawatts when the 
overhaul is completed toward the end of September. According to 
Padori, the three heat and power units that have generated 210 
megawatts each will be renovated, raising the capacity of each 
unit to 225 megawatts, thus increasing the Bitola plant's 
capacity to 675 megawatts. 
  The idea of expanding the capacity of REK "Bitola" dates 
from 
the signing of an agreement with Russian partners from Saint 
Petersburg in October by Mr. Podoljski. According to the 
assistant director of the Bitola plant, Pande Lazarevski, it is 
significant that the increased power capacity can be obtained 
with the small investment of $4.5 million, or about $100,000 per 
megawatt. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

