<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Cooperation With Austria, Hungary </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Military Cooperation With Austria, Hungary </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   94P20917A Ljubljana DNEVNIK in Slovene 18 Jun 94 p 32 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20917A </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana DNEVNIK </F>
<F P=105>  Slovene </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Miran Subic: "Our Soldiers in Austria"] </F>
  [Text] Kranj, 18 June -- History is being made today as the 
Slovene Army is about to step on Austrian soil without 
commotion. The "Chamois" (so named for their unit insignia) from 
Upper Carniola will not be there as a purely military force but 
to cooperate with the 7th Chasseur Brigade from Klagenfurt, 
thereby contributing to good relations between the two states. 
  Ten privates and 22 commissioned and noncommissioned 
officers 
will take part in the 48-km long Rosenthal March. This is the 
first time that Slovene uniformed army personnel are 
participating in such an event abroad. 
  Next week, 16 Hungarian officers will arrive at Bohinjska 
Bela to familiarize themselves with tactics and the use of 
mountain and alpine equipment in mountainous terrain. Although 
mountainous warfare is not especially developed in Hungary, this 
kind of training is a valuable form of international cooperation 
(in keeping with the saying "Hungary does not have a sea, 
however, it does have a navy"). Our excellent alpinists will 
take part in training, which will culminate in our Hungarian 
guests "capturing" Mount Triglav. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-32594 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu124_m_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-124 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ethnic Albanians Jailed for `Hostile Activity' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ethnic Albanians Jailed for `Hostile Activity' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706135994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1306 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2706135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, 27 Jun (TANJUG) -- The council of the second 
municipal court in Skopje, chaired by Ljubomir Jovevski, today 
pronounced sentences on a group of Albanians who took part in 
organizing paramilitary formations in Macedonia [FYROM -- The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia] and smuggling arms via 
Albania. The court passed sentences between five and eight years 
in jail. 
  The defendants have been sentenced for associating in order 
to engage in hostile activity. Mithat Emini, secretary general 
of the PDP [Party of Democratic Prosperity] with headquarters in 
Tetovo and Hasan Agusi, were sentenced to eight years in jail. 
Ejupi Rezni, Selam Elmazi, and Sinasi Redzepi to seven years in 
jail; Husein Haskaj, Macedonian deputy defense minister, Akif 
Demiri, and Abdiselam Arslani to six years in jail; and Burim 
Murtezani and Eugen Cami to five years in jail. Agusi will be 
expelled from Macedonia after his term in jail. 
  Under the indictment, all of the accused associated to 
engage 
in hostile activity, and they had clear aims and tasks to topple 
the fledgling Macedonian state. Emini, Agusi, and Haskaj were 
the ringleaders in this hostile activity. 
  The indictment says that the accused formed "a HQ of 
national 
defense," and Emini was candidate for the commander. They set 
up a state-of-the-art computer center and had a courier service 
in operation. They also began to draw up a program of setting 
up paramilitary units in Kumanovo and towns in western Macedonia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

