<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abdic: Izetbegovic Trying To `Liquidate' Rebels </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Abdic: Izetbegovic Trying To `Liquidate' Rebels </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706210994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2010 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706210994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Banja Luka, June 27 (TANJUG) -- The offensive of 
Moslem troops loyal to hardliner Alija Izetbegovic against the 
rebel Moslem autonomous province of western Bosnia is designed 
to stifle all life in the province and liquidate its leadership, 
says province President Fikret Abdic. 
  Abdic, Izetbegovic's moderate rival, told the local radio 
Velika Kladusa that he would organise a nation-wide resistance 
front against Izetbegovic's loyalists. He accused the Moslem 
regime in Sarajevo of a determination to crush the struggle of 
the army and people of western Bosnia for autonomy, which he 
said enjoyed the support of Moslems in the diaspora. 
  For months past, the army loyal to Izetbegovic has been 
trying to subdue the province, which was proclaimed by Abdic's 
supporters last September in opposition to the war-mongering 
policy of the regime in Sarajevo. The provincial leadership has 
signed separate peace accords with Bosnian Serbs and Croats, 
pursuing free trade with them even at the height of Moslem-Serb 
and Moslem-Croat fighting elsewhere in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

