<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims Reportedly Continue Attacks on Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims Reportedly Continue Attacks on Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706162594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1559 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2706162594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Zvornik, June 27 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Moslem forces 
have continued attacks on Bosnian Serb positions, further 
violating the one-month ceasefire that took effect on June 10, 
Bosnian Serb Army sources told TANJUG on Monday [27 June]. They 
said the heaviest Moslem attacks in the past 24 hours were in 
the areas of Doboj, Mt. Ozren in northern Bosnia and Mt. Vlasic 
in the central part of that former Yugoslav republic. 
  Early on Monday, Moslems opened artillery fire on Doboj, a 
strategically important Serb town in the Bosna River valley, 
with sporadic mortar shellings of Serb positions in the areas of 
Trebava, Mt. Ozren, Teslic and Gradacac around Doboj. Moslems 
also continued attacks on Serb positions and settlements near 
the Serb town of Brcko on the Sava River. 
  Moslems are still launching infantry attacks on Serb 
settlements of Ilidza, Nedzarici and Ilijas in the Sarajevo 
area, Bosnian Serb Army sources said. Bosnian Croats violated 
the ceasefire in the area of the Croat enclave of Orasje in 
northern Bosnia, where combined Bosnian Croat and Croatian Army 
troops are firing at Serb positions from small arms as well as 
anti-aircraft guns and mortars. 
  Croats also renewed attacks in the area between Dubrovnik 
and 
the Serb town of Trebinje in the Dubrovnik hinterland in 
southern Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

