<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman Holds Talks With Italy's Martino </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tudjman Holds Talks With Italy's Martino </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2706213894 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2000 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2706213894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Croatian President Franjo Tudjman this afternoon 
received Italian Foreign Minister Antonio Martino, who is paying 
an official visit to the Republic of Croatia at the head of a 
delegation of the Italian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the 
president's office said in a statement. 
  The talks focused on numerous issues relating to bilateral 
relations between the two states, particularly to the problem of 
the areas of the Republic of Croatia under Serb occupation and 
the resolution of the crisis in Bosnia--Herzegovina. 
Convergence of views was expressed regarding the resolution of 
some bilateral issues on the basis of friendly relations and 
mutual interests of both countries. Minister Martino's visit 
today provides guarantees for better political and economic 
relations between the two countries to be achieved through the 
spirit of the best possible understanding, the statement says. 
  Attempts should be made to resolve the crisis in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina in a peaceful way. It was stated in this 
context that steps by the so-called contact group countries and 
a meeting of the G-7 and Russia which is to take place in Naples 
at the beginning of next week are hopefully awaited. Hope was 
also expressed that the Serb occupation of areas of the Republic 
of Croatia would be resolved in a peaceful way through the 
reintegration of these areas into the state and legal system of 
the Republic of Croatia. The Republic of Italy will try to lend 
all its possible support in this respect by using its influence, 
the statement says in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

