<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zagreb Reportedly No Longer Supporting Abdic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zagreb Reportedly No Longer Supporting Abdic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2706183994 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2706183994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nada al-Isa from Zagreb] </F>
  [Text] Fikret Abdic, the rebel from the Cazin Krajina, can 
no longer count on any support from Zagreb. He has not had it 
for some time now. We were told this today exclusively for 
Radio Television Bosnia-Herzegovina by one top-level official in 
the presidential palace in Zagreb, who wished to remain 
anonymous. We can only say that he is a very well-known and 
respected politician in Zagreb, even though he is perhaps not 
the most popular one. 
  Even the Serbs from the so-called Krajina have repudiated 
Abdic, although just a year ago -- when he proclaimed autonomy 
-- they signed an agreement on military aid. However, according 
to the information in Zagreb, now they send him almost no aid, 
or so little that he can do nothing with it against the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army, that is, its 5th Corps, our source 
claims. 
  The doors to Zagreb have been closed to Abdic since the 
Washington Agreement. Our source says: The autonomy proclaimed 
in principle in western Bosnia is nearing its end. Abdic danced 
his dance of death around Kladusa and Bihac for only one summer. 
According to the information on the successes of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army 5th Corps, all of western Bosnia will 
soon be under the Sarajevo authority, says our reliable source 
from the presidential palace in Zagreb. If they knew who he 
was, both Fikret Abdic and President Tudjman would probably get 
headaches. 

</TEXT>

