<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic: Cease-Fire Depends on Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Izetbegovic: Cease-Fire Depends on Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2706150994 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2706150994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Alija Izetbegovic, president of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency, received today General Michael 
Rose, commander of the UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, at his request. Army General Rasim Delic, 
chief of staff of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army, and Viktor 
Andreyev, chief of the UNPROFOR civilian sector for 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, also attended the talks. General Rose 
complained about the increase in the number of attacks on 
UNPROFOR by both sides. 
  President Izetbegovic said that our policy is full 
cooperation with UNPROFOR, and that everything will be done to 
provide them with normal conditions for work. He stressed that 
the cease-fire had to hold on the entire territory of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, and not partially, as it suits the 
aggressor. Military observers for the monitoring of the 
cease-fire should be deployed in a reciprocal fashion on both 
our and the aggressors' side, but the presence of the 
aggressor's liaison officers on our territory is unacceptable. 
  General Rose said that intensive work was under way in 
Gorazde to solve the problems with the return of the population 
to their homes in the zone within 3 km. Asked by Rose about the 
possibility of extending the cease-fire for another four weeks, 
President Izetbegovic said that this would depend on the 
progress made in the political negotiations. 

</TEXT>

