<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-125 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ALBANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Independent Press Seen as `Small Minority' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Independent Press Seen as `Small Minority' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2806134094 Tirana GAZETA SHQIPTARE in Albanian 24 Jun 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> AU2806134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana GAZETA SHQIPTARE </F>
<F P=105>  Albanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tirana -- The development and current situation of 
the free press in Albania, based on the experience of Albanian 
journalists themselves, was the topic of a discussion held in 
the Palace of Congresses with a group of Albanian journalists 
representing various newspapers, organized by the delegation of 
European Democratic Union -- of which Professor Doctor Andreas 
Khol was a member. 
  Acknowledging the birth of a free press in Albania over the 
last few years, the journalists highlighted in their discussions 
the existence of a dual tendency: on the one hand, abuse of the 
freedom of the press and, on the other, efforts to restrict it. 
Some of the speakers pointed out that the media in general was 
still politicized, and the independent press remained a small 
minority. 
  It is precisely the latter -- having financial support from 
neither political forces nor government -- that is extremely 
endangered by the merciless law of insolvency of the market 
economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

