<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Justice Minister Resigns in Housing Scandal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Justice Minister Resigns in Housing Scandal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806195194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1916 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806195194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ljubljana, June 28 (TANJUG) -- Slovene Justice 
Minister Miha Kozinc resigned over his role in a scandal which 
involved exploiting legal loopholes to give extremely favourable 
housing credits to state officials. 
  Kozinc, who chaired the government's housing commission, 
resigned under pressure from the public indignant that officials 
in newly-independent Slovenia should have greater privileges 
than those enjoyed by functionaries in the defunct communist 
regime. 
  The commission was paying out up to 100,000 Deutsche marks' 
worth of housing credits from the state budget at interest rates 
one-sixth of those paid by the man in the street for a housing 
credit from a commercial bank. 
  The favourable credits were used for a variety of purposes 
other than housing, such as building a swimming pool in the 
pation in the case of rightist M.P. Irena Oman. Kozinc himself 
benefited from the scheme to the tune of 70,000 Deutsche marks 
in housing credits. 
  Kozinc is the fifth minister to resign from the cabinet of 
Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek in recent months, which means that 
one-third of the ministers have been replaced under a cloud. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

