<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Demands Respect for `Just Victory' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic Demands Respect for `Just Victory' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806170794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1618 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806170794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Bileca, June 28 (TANJUG) -- If the international 
community wants peace, it will have to respect the Serbs' just 
victory because they have remained on their territories, Bosnian 
Serb leader Radovan Karadzic said Tuesday. The Bosnian Serbs 
now control 70 percent of the territory of the former Yugoslav 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina while according to land 
registration documents they owned 64 percent of the republican 
territory before the war. 
  Under the international plan, the Bosnian Serb Republic is 
to 
get 49 percent of the Bosnian territory and the Moslem-Croat 
Federation 51 percent. 
  If the international community does not want peace, it will 
again, like on earlier occasions, offer unacceptable maps and 
humiliating conditions to the Serb victorious army, knowing that 
the Serbs will reject such a plan, Karadzic said at a ceremony 
in a Bileca army barracks marking the day of the Bosnian Serb 
army. 
  "If the maps are in any way acceptable, we will have them 
for 
the love of our brothers in Serbia and Montenegro, but only 
under the condition that the sanctions be lifted, which will 
have to be included in the peace document," Karadzic said in the 
eastern Herzegovina town Bileca. 
  In May 1992, the United Nations imposed tough economic and 
political sanctions on Yugoslavia because of alleged involvement 
in the civil war in the territory of the former Yugoslav 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  If the international "Contact Group" for Bosnia comes with 
unacceptable maps, Serbia and Montenegro will not insist that we 
accept them, Karadzic said and added that, like in earlier 
occasions, they would stand firmly by the Bosnian Serbs. 
  The general staff commander of the Bosnian Serb army, 
Colonel-General Ratko Mladic said the Serbs "want peace with all 
their hearts but not any peace and not at any cost." 
  The Serbs want "honourable and digified peace respecting the 
results of our struggles over the centuries and in this latest 
war, our victories and our past and present rights." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

