<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Claim Muslims Attacking Bihac Front </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Claim Muslims Attacking Bihac Front </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906004394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2321 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906004394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, June 28 (TANJUG) -- Moslems have been 
fiercely attacking from mortars and all arms all along the Bihac 
front in northwestern Bosnia since morning, Bosnian Serb army 
sources said on Tuesday. 
  The local Serb army command reported Moslem troop movements 
along most lines of separation, which is another proof that 
forces loyal to Moslem hardliner Alija Izetbegovic do not care 
for a ceasefire. 
  In the northeast, Moslem troops are keeping up a continuous 
stream of attacks on the serb positions near Doboj and on Mt 
Ozren in violation of the latest truce, which came into effect 
on June 10. 
  Moslem commander Rasim Delic said last week that his troops 
were waging an offensive war, prompting Bosnian Serb President 
Radovan Karadzic to warn on Saturday that the Serbs would launch 
a counter-offensive if the Moslem attacks continued. 
  "I am alarmed that this upsurge in fighting threatens the 
prospects for reaching a comprehensive cessation of hostilities 
and undermines efforts already under way to broker an overall 
political settlement," U.N. Special Envoy to Former Yugoslavia 
Yasushi Akashi said in Sarajevo before leaving for a meeting at 
NATO headquarters in Brussels. 
  U.N. commander for Bosnia-Herzegovina, General Sir Michael 
Rose, said before leaving for Brussels on Tuesday that the 
Moslem side "is the one that has been most hostile to the peace 
process and constantly breaching the ceasefire." 
  "The danger is that they will provoke a massive Serb 
response," Rose added. 
  Akashi and Rose will discuss with NATO leaders possibilities 
for coordinated U.N. and NATO action in case of both acceptance 
and refusal of an international peace offer by the Bosnian 
belligerents, Reuters said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

