Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Sets Defense Sector Targets </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister Sets Defense Sector Targets </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906092194 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 0600 
GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2906092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government has approved the final version of a 
document entitled "The Fundamental Issues of Poland's Defense." 
The text does not contain a clause on the superiority over 
armed forces. The National Defense Committee [KOK] has excluded 
this issue for separate examination. National Defense Minister 
Piotr Kolodziejczyk, when presenting the guidelines of the 
document on the fundamental issues of Poland's defense, said 
that it would be possible to embark on modernizing the Polish 
Army when the state budget expenditure on defense reaches the 
level of 3 percent of the gross domestic product. At present, 
the Ministry's budget stands at 2.1 percent of the state budget 
expenditure. 
  Minister Kolodziejczyk believes that, if expenditure on the 
Army is increased by 0.3 percent each year, the Polish Army will 
achieve Western standards in 20 years. 
  [Begin Kolodziejczyk recording] The pace of technological 
modernization within the armed forces will depend on the amount 
of money guaranteed by the budget. We are pressing for 3 
percent of the gross domestic product. Only then will we be 
able to say that we are embarking on a gradual, slow, 20-year 
process of modernizing the Army. The modernization should bring 
our technological standards up to those of Western armies in 
roughly the year 2015. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

