<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Two Hungarian Parties Sign Coalition Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Two Hungarian Parties Sign Coalition Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2806131494 Bratislava SLOVENSKY DENNIK in Slovak 25 Jun 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU2806131494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava SLOVENSKY DENNIK </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "vg": "Talks With the Hungarian Civic Party Can </F>
Begin; Miklos Duray and Vojtech Bugar Signed Coalition Agreement 
Between Coexistence and the Hungarian Christian Democratic 
Movement"] 
  [Text] Bratislava--Miklos Duray, chairman of the 
Coexistence movement, and Vojtech Bugar, chairman of the 
Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement [MKDH], signed a 
coalition agreement yesterday. As Miklos Duray stated at a 
subsequent briefing, the aim of the coalition agreement is the 
formation of a political alliance that will be able, in a 
political struggle, to develop the law-governed state and 
strengthen democratic forces. The coalition partners agreed on 
close postelection cooperation in and outside parliament, as 
well as on the establishment of joint committees for the 
coordination of policies in the spheres of self-administration, 
economy, and education. According to Vojtech Bugar, the 
agreement is a preparation for postelection scenarios and is 
designed to meet the expectations of Hungarian voters. The 
agreement is subject to ratification by the supreme bodies of 
both political entities. Both chairmen stressed that the 
political part of the agreement would be published in full, 
while the publication of its other parts, as well as the number 
of parliamentary clubs, will still be subject to talks. 
  As the MKDH chairman went on to say, the agreement provides 
for the possibility of another partner entering this coalition; 
talks on the possibility of expanding the coalition with the 
Hungarian Civic Party [MOS] opened yesterday. In the event of 
agreement with MOS, a new coalition agreement will be signed, 
which will also contain a section anchoring "very close 
cooperation. Such cooperation is necessary because we know 
that, during the two years of the Hungarian coalition's 
existence, there have been various attempts to break it up," the 
MKDH chairman added. 
  Responding to the demand of MOS Chairman L. Nagy for a 
25-percent representation of his party on the common slate of 
candidates, as this corresponds to the number of "Hungarian" 
votes MOS won in the last elections, Vojtech Bugar said that 
proceeding from the results of two years ago was unthinkable. 
Miklos Duray even qualified this condition as ridiculous. 

</TEXT>

