<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hungarians Prefer Moderates to `Radical' Duray </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hungarians Prefer Moderates to `Radical' Duray </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2806134194 Bratislava SLOVENSKY DENNIK in Slovak 25 Jun 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> AU2806134194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava SLOVENSKY DENNIK </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "ze": "Vojtech Bugar in First Position"] </F>
  [Text] The editorial office of [Hungarian-language Slovak 
daily] UJ SZO asked its readers in which Hungarian politician in 
Slovakia they have the most confidence. According to the 1,153 
responses received, the largest number of votes, 798, went to 
[Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement Chairman, MKDH] Vojtech 
Bugar. [Chairman of the MKDH parliamentary group] Pal Csaky was 
second, with 683 votes; [Coexistence Deputy Chairman] Arpad 
Duka-Zolyomi third, with 492 votes; [Coexistence Chairman] 
Miklos Duray fourth, with 357 votes; and [Hungarian Civic Party, 
MOS, Chairman] Laszlo Nagy fifth, with 257 readers' votes. 
Similarly, the MKDH received from the readers of the 
Hungarian-language daily 533 votes; Coexistence was second, with 
380 votes, and MOS third, with 231. The editorial team does not 
claim that the survey was representative. Nonetheless, it is 
interesting and, for the uninitiated, perhaps even surprising 
that Miklos Duray finished only in fourth place and was even 
overtaken by his party colleague Arpad Duka-Zolyomi. Vojtech 
Bugar's popularity is the result of his politically prudent 
decisions. When we consider that it is the result of a 
longer-term trend, it also signals that our Hungarian fellow 
citizens prefer a realistic policy to a radical one. 

</TEXT>

