<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Italy's Martino Visits, Discusses Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Italy's Martino Visits, Discusses Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Martino Meets With Milosevic </H4>

<F P=102> LD2806122394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1115 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806122394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 28 Jun (TANJUG) -- Serbian President 
Slobodan Milosevic today received Italian Foreign Minister 
Antonio Martino, who is paying a visit to the Federal Republic 
of Yugoslavia [FRY]. 
  In the course of cordial and open talks the president of 
Serbia and the Italian foreign minister exchanged views on 
questions of interest for the further successful development of 
bilateral relations and cooperation, as well as those of 
significance for the resolution of the Yugoslav crisis, and 
peace and security in the region, reads a statement issued by 
President Milosevic's office. 
  Foreign Minister Martino expressed the readiness and desire 
of the Italian Government to become involved in activities aimed 
at overcoming the crisis in the region. Italy is interested in 
a stable development of cooperation and good-neighborly 
relations with the FRY, with particular emphasis on the interest 
both countries have in strengthening economic links. It is a 
fact that the economic sanctions against the FRY delayed 
realization of many joint projects, which has harmed not only 
the economies of Serbia and the FRY, but also of a number of 
other countries with which Serbia and the FRY are linked and 
interdependent on, to a high degree. Economic sanctions are an 
obstacle imposed on free exchange of goods, circulation of 
people and ideas, their free exchange and communication, and for 
this reason they have to be lifted as soon as possible as 
unreasonable and discriminatory measures that affect the 
interests of several countries, the statement notes. 
  The peace process and activities aimed at ending the war in 
the former Bosnia-Herzegovina were discussed in particular. It 
was stated that the international community undoubtedly has the 
responsibility and an obligation to use its influence in a 
determined manner with the aim of having the Muslim side end 
armed provocations and threats, and to finally give up 
aspirations to achieve its goals by war. 
  In the interest of peace the international community has 
high 
responsibility for presenting an overall plan which would not be 
based on an one-sided approach and favoring the interests of one 
side in the conflict at the expense of the other, but on the 
principles of equality, equal protection of their vital 
interests and an unbiased treatment. In keeping with this, 
Serbia believes that the principle of equality -- which has to 
be respected -- also implies the lifting of the economic 
sanctions. 
  Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic also attended 
the talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

