<H3> <TI>   CDR Chairman on Iliescu Impeachment, Censure </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CDR Chairman on Iliescu Impeachment, Censure </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2506173294 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1412 GMT 25 Jun 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2506173294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 25/6/1994 -- "Political 
undertakings initiated by the Democratic Convention of Romania 
[CDR] regarding a suspension from office of President Ion 
Iliescu and a vote of no-confidence prove the ability of this 
political alliance to act in the interest of the citizens," CDR 
President Emil Constantinescu told a news conference held 
Saturday, 25 June, in Bucharest. 
  "Incitement of local authorities not to put into application 
final court decisions as well as President Iliescu's refusal to 
give an explanation before Parliament are also violations of the 
Constitution and of the principles of democracy," according to 
Emil Constantinescu. 
  As for the censure motion, the CDR front-ranker said that 
"it 
first of all aims to bring a normal terming to the dialogue 
between the government and the country's citizens." 
  Asked about divergent opinions within the alliance, Emil 
Constantinescu and the representatives of other parties in the 
alliance admitted that "several divergent opinions are 
persisting within the convention" which prove, however, the 
democratic spirit of the alliance. While liberal Dinu Patriciu 
has drawn attention on the need for the convention "to become a 
homogeneous political party, a powerful decision-making 
structure" and a right-wing force, Civic Alliance Party 
front-ranker Emil Tocaci considered that tensions within the CDR 
have been magnified, for the convention "will further be a 
reality of the Romanian political life." 

</TEXT>

