  [Text] Pernik, June 26 (BTA) -- Considering the conditions 
and the way in which the census in Macedonia [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] is being conducted, the 
lack of normal conditions for the expression of ethnic identity, 
the curtailment of freedom of speech and the expression of 
personal views and critical statements, considering certain 
facts of police coercion, and the open anti-Bulgarian campaign 
waged by the government-controlled media, I cannot accept the 
results of the census as objective and accurate, Nikolay 
Slatinski MP, chairman of Parliament's National Security 
Committee, told BTA. 
  He said he expressed his personal view. The official 
government position is delayed, obscure and inadequate, 
according to him. According to him, the policy pursued by the 
Macedonian authorities, of putting obstacles to normal 
good-neighbourly relations, could lead to a review of the 
Bulgarian position, and a firmer Bulgarian stand on Macedonia. 

</TEXT>

